"""
MKT Christ — Exodus chapters 16–18
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-exodus-16-18.py

Chapter coverage:
  ch16 = 36 verses — manna and quail in the wilderness
  ch17 = 16 verses — water from the rock; defeat of Amalek
  ch18 = 27 verses — Jethro's visit; judicial organization

Key typological decisions:
- Manna: John 6 makes the direct type explicit; every manna verse is shaped
  by that interpretive key; the hidden manna of Rev 2:17 and the golden jar
  in the ark (Heb 9:4) are secondary NT anchors
- The rock of ch17: 1 Cor 10:4 identifies it as Christ directly; the strike-
  and-water pattern reads as the crucifixion/outpouring of the Spirit
- Moses's raised hands (17:11-12): intercession theme; Heb 7:25 is the
  canonical NT articulation of what Moses's posture points toward
- Jethro (ch18): a Gentile who acknowledges YHWH as greatest of all gods;
  treated as a shadow of Gentile inclusion without over-reading
- ch16 v15 already present; merge_comm skips it safely
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS_CHRIST = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>A theme: Israel in the wilderness between liberation and inheritance. Jesus's forty-day wilderness fast (Matt 4:1-2) recapitulates Israel's forty-year wilderness journey, compressing it into the life of the true Israel. The wilderness is not an accident but the appointed school of dependence — the place where Egypt's self-sufficiency is unlearned before Canaan's abundance is entered.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A theme: the grumbling of the redeemed. The people who saw the exodus signs now quarrel against Moses and Aaron. This pattern of unbelief among the delivered is the pattern Paul cites as a warning to the church (1 Cor 10:10): 'do not grumble, as some of them did.' The Passover has occurred; the wilderness testing has begun. The same sequence — redemption followed by testing and grumbling — marks the post-baptism life of the Christian community (1 Cor 10:1-4).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A theme: the desire to return to bondage. 'Would that we had died by the hand of YHWH in the land of Egypt' — the imagination that slavery with food is better than freedom with hunger. Jesus addresses the same logic when he warns against double-mindedness: you cannot serve God and mammon (Matt 6:24). The pull back to Egypt is the pull back to the flesh-security that the old life offered.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A direct type: the bread from heaven. YHWH says 'I am about to rain bread (<em>lechem</em>) from heaven for you.' Jesus in John 6:32-35 takes this verse as his direct text: 'Moses did not give you the bread from heaven, but my Father gives you the true bread from heaven. For the bread of God is he who comes down from heaven and gives life to the world.' The manna is explicitly identified by Jesus as a type of himself; every subsequent manna verse carries this Johannine interpretive key.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A shadow: the double provision before the Sabbath. The double portion of manna on the sixth day, requiring no going out on the seventh, anticipates the Sabbath rest that remains for the people of God (Heb 4:9-11). Christ, as the one who fulfills the Sabbath's promise (Matt 11:28-29, 'come to me and I will give you rest'), is the substance behind the Sabbath-provision pattern.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A revelation of God: 'You shall know that it was YHWH who brought you out of the land of Egypt.' The miracle of provision in the wilderness is designed not merely to sustain life but to produce knowledge — the recognition formula central to the plague narrative. Christ is the final revelation that ensures the recognition: 'Whoever has seen me has seen the Father' (John 14:9).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A revelation of God: the glory of YHWH will be seen in the morning. The morning-glory pattern anticipates the resurrection morning; John's Gospel consistently places resurrection manifestations 'in the morning' (20:1). The glory that satisfies hunger in the wilderness anticipates the glory that gives eternal life through the resurrection.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Your grumbling is not against us but against YHWH.' The identity between the mediator and the one who sent him — established here for Moses — is perfected in Christ, who says 'Whoever rejects me rejects him who sent me' (Luke 10:16; John 13:20). The divine claim on Israel's complaint exposes the theological depth of rejection.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Come near before YHWH, for he has heard your grumbling.' The call to draw near to God despite grumbling — the invitation to approach is not withdrawn — anticipates Hebrews' call to 'draw near with confidence to the throne of grace' (Heb 4:16). The access that YHWH does not rescind from grumbling Israel is secured permanently in Christ.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A revelation of God: the glory of YHWH appears in the cloud. The <em>kavod</em> in the cloud is the same theophanic presence that Moses will ask to see fully in Exod 33:18 and that John identifies with Christ: 'The Word became flesh and dwelt (tabernacled) among us, and we have seen his glory (<em>doxa</em>)' (John 1:14).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A revelation of God: YHWH speaks in response to grumbling with provision, not punishment. The divine hearing of murmuring and the response of generosity rather than wrath reveals the character of God that reaches its fullest expression in Christ's patience toward unbelief (2 Pet 3:9).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A direct type: 'I have heard the grumbling of the people of Israel. Say to them: at twilight you shall eat meat, and in the morning you shall be filled with bread.' The feeding of Israel in the wilderness with both meat and bread at appointed times prefigures the two feeding miracles (the feeding of the 5000 with bread, John 6; and the post-resurrection breakfast of fish, John 21:9-13) by which the risen Christ feeds his people.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: quails cover the camp at evening. The quails are the less-typologized element of the wilderness provision; their abundance at evening and disappearance by morning is simply God's gift of protein to a people who cannot hunt in the wilderness. As a shadow, the satisfaction of Israel's deepest hunger-cry points to Christ who says 'whoever comes to me shall not hunger' (John 6:35).</p>",
    "14": "<p>A direct type: thin, flake-like substance on the ground — 'fine as hoarfrost on the ground.' The appearance of manna as something small, unrecognizable, on the ground, requiring stooping to gather, anticipates Christ's humility: 'though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor' (2 Cor 8:9). The bread from heaven came in the form of a thing that required the people to bow down and collect it from the earth.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A direct type: 'Gather of it, each one of you, as much as he can eat.' The manna is gathered in proportion to personal need, not relative merit or social status. Christ is the bread of life given to each person who comes in faith — 'whoever comes to me I will never cast out' (John 6:37). The invitation is proportioned to hunger, not to deserving.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A direct type: 'The people of Israel did so. They gathered, some more, some less.' The different quantities gathered by different people — yet all finding their need met (v18) — prefigures the diverse measures of faith and maturity in the body of Christ, in whom all find adequate supply (Eph 4:7, 'grace was given to each one of us according to the measure of Christ's gift').</p>",
    "18": "<p>A direct type: 'Whoever gathered much had nothing left over, and whoever gathered little had no lack.' Paul cites this verse directly in 2 Cor 8:15 as the scriptural basis for the principle of Christian generosity equalizing abundance and need. The manna's leveling miracle is the Old Testament economic theology behind the Jerusalem community's sharing in Acts 2:44-45 and the Corinthian collection for the poor saints.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A theme: 'Let no one leave any of it till the morning.' The prohibition on hoarding points to the principle of daily dependence on God for provision, which Jesus encodes in the Lord's Prayer: 'Give us today our daily (<em>epiousios</em>) bread' (Matt 6:11). Manna cannot be stored; the bread from heaven is for daily receiving, not for hoarding against an uncertain future.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A theme: stored manna rots and breeds worms. Those who disobeyed and stored overnight found corruption. The contrast with Christ, who is the bread 'which will last to eternal life' (John 6:27), is explicit in John 6:49: 'Your fathers ate the manna in the wilderness and they died.' The temporal manna decays; the eternal bread does not.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A shadow: manna melted when the sun grew hot. The perishability of the manna in the heat points to what Jesus says in John 6:49-51: the manna was temporary — those who ate it died anyway. He is the bread that does not melt away, the bread that gives eternal life, not merely temporal sustenance. The contrast between melting manna and eternal bread is the heart of the Bread of Life discourse.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A shadow: double portion on the sixth day in preparation for the Sabbath. The Sabbath provision — doubled bread with no gathering needed on the seventh day — prefigures Christ as the final Sabbath rest. Hebrews 4:3-11 interprets the Sabbath as a future reality pointing to the rest that remains for those who believe. Christ fulfills the Sabbath's promise (Matt 11:28-30).</p>",
    "23": "<p>A shadow: 'Tomorrow is a day of solemn rest, a holy Sabbath to YHWH.' The Sabbath is the day when normal provision-gathering ceases and the double portion stored on the sixth day sustains. As a type, the Sabbath provision requires receiving on the day before and resting in what has been given — the pattern of faith: not continual striving but trust in the provision already secured.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A shadow: the Sabbath manna does not rot or breed worms. What decays on other days does not decay on the Sabbath. The incorruptibility of the Sabbath manna anticipates Christ's resurrection incorruption — Acts 2:27 quotes Ps 16:10 'you will not let your Holy One see decay,' applying it to Jesus. The Sabbath bread that cannot rot prefigures the Bread of Life who could not be held by death.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A theme: 'Eat it today, for today is a Sabbath to YHWH; today you will not find it in the field.' The Sabbath rest requires trusting that what was given is sufficient; no additional provision-seeking is needed. The 'today' emphasis in the Epistle to the Hebrews — 'Today, if you hear his voice, do not harden your hearts' (Heb 3:7,13,15) — carries the same urgency of receiving what God provides in the appointed day.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A shadow: six days to gather, none on the seventh. The Sabbath pattern embedded in manna-gathering structures Israel's time around a weekly rhythm of work and rest. Christ fulfills and reorients the Sabbath in his resurrection on the first day of the week — the Lord's Day becomes the weekly memorial of the new creation, the eighth-day eschatology that transcends the seven-day creation cycle.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A theme: some went out on the Sabbath to gather and found nothing. The refusal to trust the double-portion provision leads to fruitless seeking. Jesus addresses the same pattern: those who seek provision through works of law rather than through faith in him find that the manna of divine grace has already been given; their self-sufficient gathering produces nothing (John 6:28-29).</p>",
    "28": "<p>A revelation of God: 'How long will you refuse to keep my commandments and my instructions?' The divine question identifies Sabbath-breaking as a form of refusing God's instruction — a covenantal failure with deeper roots than mere calendar violation. The refusal to rest in God's provision is the refusal to trust the God who provides. Christ's teaching on anxiety (Matt 6:25-34) addresses the same spiritual root.</p>",
    "29": "<p>A revelation of God: 'See! YHWH has given you the Sabbath.' The Sabbath is explicitly God's gift (<em>natan</em>, he gave), not merely a burden. The double portion on the sixth day is God's provision for Sabbath rest; the Sabbath is structured into creation as grace, not law. Christ's statement 'The Sabbath was made for man' (Mark 2:27) retrieves this gift-character of the Sabbath against its legalistic hardening.</p>",
    "30": "<p>A shadow: the people rested on the seventh day. The Sabbath rest of all Israel in the wilderness — for once, all obeying, all resting — points toward the eschatological rest of Hebrews 4:9-11: 'there remains a Sabbath rest for the people of God.' The perfect communal rest of the wilderness Sabbath is a foretaste of the final rest that Christ secures for his people.</p>",
    "31": "<p>A revelation of God: 'It was like coriander seed, white, and the taste of it was like wafers made with honey.' The manna's sweetness recalls Ps 34:8 — 'Taste and see that YHWH is good' — and anticipates Ps 119:103 — 'How sweet are your words to my taste, sweeter than honey to my mouth.' Christ as the Word made flesh is the ultimate sweetness of divine provision; the Bread of Life is not merely sustaining but delightful.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A shadow: 'Let an omer of it be kept throughout your generations, so that they may see the bread with which I fed you in the wilderness.' The preserved manna — kept as a perpetual witness — is placed in the golden jar that is kept in the ark (Heb 9:4). Revelation 2:17 promises 'to the one who conquers I will give some of the hidden manna' — the manna in the ark as a type of the hidden, preserved, eternal life in Christ that awaits the overcomer.</p>",
    "33": "<p>A shadow: Aaron takes an omer and places it before the testimony to be kept. The manna before the testimony — in the presence of the covenant — anticipates Christ as the bread of the new covenant (Luke 22:19, 'Do this in remembrance of me'), whose body is the new covenant memorial that replaces the manna-jar as the perpetual witness of divine provision.</p>",
    "34": "<p>A shadow: the jar of manna is placed before the testimony, preserved in the ark (Heb 9:4 lists it among the ark's contents). The hidden manna that cannot be seen by ordinary worshippers — inaccessible in the Holy of Holies — points to the 'hidden wisdom' of Christ, 'in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge' (Col 2:3), accessible only through faith.</p>",
    "35": "<p>A direct type: Israel ate manna forty years until they came to the border of Canaan. The forty years of manna-eating is Israel's entire wilderness generation — a lifetime of daily dependence on bread from heaven. Jesus's forty days of fasting (Matt 4:2) recapitulate this forty-year period in concentrated form, and his refusal to turn stones into bread ('Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that comes from the mouth of God,' Matt 4:4, quoting Deut 8:3) rejects the manna-substitute and affirms the true bread of God's word.</p>",
    "36": "<p>A revelation of God: the measure of the omer — one-tenth of an ephah. The precise measure of daily provision points to the divine exactness in caring for Israel: not an arbitrary amount but a measured sufficiency for each person. This precision reveals a God who knows and meets each person's need — the Father who knows what his children need before they ask (Matt 6:8,32).</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>A theme: 'but there was no water for the people to drink.' The wilderness water crisis follows the manna provision — the test shifts from food to water. The sequence (no bread, then no water) escalates Israel's dependence. In John 4:10-14, Jesus offers living water to one who is thirsty; in John 7:37-38, 'If anyone thirsts, let him come to me and drink.' The thirst of the wilderness is the Old Testament form of the soul's deepest need that only Christ can satisfy.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A theme: the people quarreled with Moses and demanded water. The quarrel (<em>yariv</em>) at Rephidim is the same verb that gives the place its secondary name Meribah (quarrel). Hebrews 3:7-11 and Psalm 95:8 use Meribah as the defining image of hardened unbelief: 'Do not harden your hearts as in the rebellion, on the day of testing in the wilderness.' The water-quarrel becomes the canonical NT case study of what resistance to Christ looks like in the redeemed community.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Why did you bring us up out of Egypt, to kill us and our children and our livestock with thirst?' The extreme accusation — Moses brought them out to murder them — reveals how quickly human gratitude evaporates under pressure. God hears this too-far accusation and provides water anyway. The pattern is Christ on the cross: praying for those who crucify him (Luke 23:34), providing for those who reject him.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A revelation of God: Moses cries to YHWH, 'What shall I do with this people? They are almost ready to stone me.' The mediator in mortal danger interceding for the people who threaten him anticipates Christ, the stoned prophet (Matt 21:35-39, the parable of the tenants whose son is killed), praying for those who stone him. Stephen (Acts 7:59-60), imitating Christ, is stoned while praying for his killers.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A direct type: 'Go on before the people, taking with you some of the elders of Israel, and take in your hand the staff with which you struck the Nile, and go.' The staff that struck the Nile and brought plagues is now applied to the rock. In Paul's typological logic (1 Cor 10:4), the same Christ who brought judgment on Egypt brings life to Israel from the rock. The instrument of judgment and the instrument of provision are the same.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A direct type: 'Behold, I will stand before you there on the rock at Horeb, and you shall strike the rock, and water shall come out of it, and the people will drink.' Paul declares in 1 Cor 10:4: 'they drank from the spiritual Rock that followed them, and the Rock was Christ.' The rock is struck (as Christ was struck — crucified), and water flows from it (as the Spirit is poured out from Christ — John 7:38-39; John 19:34). The rock is not merely a location but a person: 'the Rock was Christ.'</p>",
    "7": "<p>A theme: the place is named Massah (testing) and Meribah (quarreling) because of the quarrel and testing of YHWH. Psalm 95:8-11 and Hebrews 3:7-19 use these names as shorthand for the hardened heart that refuses to trust. The testing at Meribah becomes the canonical Old Testament case study of apostasy: the people who were redeemed, who ate and drank spiritual food and drink from Christ (1 Cor 10:3-4), can still fall in the wilderness through unbelief.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A theme: Amalek came and fought with Israel at Rephidim. The attack from Amalek — Israel's perennial enemy — introduces the theme of spiritual warfare that runs through the entire biblical narrative. Paul describes the Christian life as warfare against principalities and powers (Eph 6:10-17); John's Revelation depicts the ongoing war of the Lamb against the beast. Amalek is the first of many adversaries whose ultimate defeat in Christ is prefigured here.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: Moses said to Joshua, 'Choose us some men, and go out and fight with Amalek. Tomorrow I will stand on the top of the hill with the staff of God in my hand.' Moses and Joshua together defeat Amalek — Moses interceding from the hill, Joshua fighting in the valley. The pairing anticipates the relationship between Christ's intercessory work in heaven (Heb 7:25, 'always living to make intercession') and the church's warfare on earth.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: Joshua fought while Moses, Aaron, and Hur went up to the top of the hill. The division of roles — intercession above, battle below — is the structure of the entire Christian life: Christ enthroned and interceding (Rom 8:34; Heb 7:25), the church fighting the spiritual battle below. The army cannot prevail without the intercessor; the intercessor does not replace the army's fighting.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A shadow: 'Whenever Moses held up his hand, Israel prevailed, and whenever he lowered his hand, Amalek prevailed.' The raised hands of Moses are the decisive factor in the battle. The typological tradition consistently reads raised hands as intercession (cf. 1 Tim 2:8, 'lifting holy hands'). Moses's raised hands prefigure Christ's perpetual intercession (Heb 7:25) that sustains the victory of God's people against all opposition.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A shadow: Moses's hands grew heavy; Aaron and Hur held them up. The two men — one on each side — holding Moses's hands steady until sunset so that Joshua prevailed has been read typologically as the supporting work of the Holy Spirit and the communion of saints in sustaining the church's prayer. More directly, it reveals that the intercession that saves God's people required human support — anticipating the incarnation, in which God takes on human weakness to sustain human salvation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A theme: Joshua defeated Amalek and his people with the edge of the sword. The sword as the instrument of God's warfare anticipates the 'sword of the Spirit, which is the word of God' (Eph 6:17) and the sword that proceeds from the mouth of Christ in Rev 19:15,21. The decisive weapon is always the word of God, even when it takes the form of a physical sword.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A theme: YHWH commands Moses to write this in a book as a memorial — 'I will utterly blot out the memory of Amalek from under heaven.' The divine record-keeping of the victory over Amalek anticipates the books opened at the final judgment (Rev 20:12) and the book of life in which the names of the redeemed are written. The war against Amalek is a chapter in YHWH's book of history; the ultimate chapter is the defeat of all evil at Christ's return (Rev 19:11-21).</p>",
    "15": "<p>A revelation of God: Moses built an altar and called it 'YHWH is my banner (<em>YHWH Nissi</em>).' The divine name YHWH-Nissi — YHWH is our ensign/standard — is the name of the victory that was won by God's power, not Israel's. The altar-naming after a military victory by God's name rather than the commander's name is a pattern of doxological warfare: victory belongs to God. Christ is the standard raised up for the nations (Isa 11:10, 'the root of Jesse, who shall stand as a signal for the peoples').</p>",
    "16": "<p>A theme: 'A hand upon the throne of YHWH! YHWH will have war with Amalek from generation to generation.' The ongoing nature of the war — from generation to generation — frames Amalek as a permanent representative of the opposition to God's kingdom, not merely a historical enemy. Revelation 19-20 places the final battle against the beast and all who oppose the Lamb as the culmination of this generational warfare that YHWH declared at Rephidim.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>A shadow: Jethro, priest of Midian and Moses's father-in-law, heard all that God had done for Moses and for Israel. Jethro is a Gentile who acknowledges YHWH on the basis of what he hears about the exodus — he responds to testimony. This pattern anticipates the Gentile mission: 'faith comes from hearing, and hearing through the word of Christ' (Rom 10:17). The Gentile who hears and comes prefigures the nations' response to the gospel proclamation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A shadow: Jethro brings Zipporah (Moses's wife, sent back earlier) and Moses's two sons to the wilderness. The reunion of Moses with his family from Midian — a Gentile household joining the covenant people at Sinai — anticipates the ingathering of the scattered and the union of families across ethnic lines in the body of Christ (Eph 2:11-18, the dividing wall removed).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A theme: Moses's sons Gershom ('sojourner there') and Eliezer ('my God is help'). The names carry the theological freight of the entire exodus: Gershom names the sojourner-condition of exile from which Moses was saved; Eliezer names the divine rescue. Both dimensions — the human condition of alien-ness and the divine intervention that saves — are inscribed in the children Moses brings to Sinai.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A revelation of God: 'My God is help (<em>Eliezer</em>), for the God of my father was my help, and delivered me from the sword of Pharaoh.' The divine name embedded in the child's name is a perpetual confession of the exodus rescue — a walking theological statement that the God who delivered Moses is the helper of the vulnerable. Christ as the one who 'helps Abraham's offspring' (Heb 2:16) fulfills this helper-theology in its ultimate form.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A shadow: Jethro comes with Moses's wife and sons to the wilderness where Moses is camped, by the mountain of God. The Gentile's journey to the mountain of God anticipates Isaiah 2:2-3 — 'many peoples shall come and say: come, let us go up to the mountain of YHWH' — and the eschatological pilgrimage of the nations to Christ (Rev 21:24-26, 'the nations will walk by its light').</p>",
    "6": "<p>A revelation of God: Jethro sends word ahead — 'I, your father-in-law Jethro, am coming to you with your wife and her two sons with her.' The advance announcement of arrival is a courtesy that implies mutual respect and anticipation. The relational texture of the Jethro narrative humanizes the story: the great lawgiver has family, has a Gentile father-in-law who loves him. Christ's own genealogy includes Gentile women (Matt 1:5), and the incarnation was itself an advance-announced arrival (Isa 7:14).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A theme: Moses went out to meet his father-in-law, bowed down, and kissed him. Moses, YHWH's greatest servant, prostrates himself before a Gentile — a gesture of genuine honor that transcends ethnic hierarchy. The mutual honor between Jew and Gentile that the gospel creates (Eph 2:11-22) is prefigured in the remarkable image of Israel's lawgiver bowing before a Midianite priest.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A revelation of God: Moses told Jethro all that YHWH had done to Pharaoh and Egypt for Israel's sake, all the hardship they had faced, and how YHWH had delivered them. Moses's recounting of the exodus — the first sustained evangelistic proclamation in the Torah — is directed to a Gentile. The content: what YHWH did, the hardship endured, and the deliverance accomplished. This is the structure of all subsequent gospel proclamation: problem, cross, resurrection.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A shadow: Jethro rejoiced for all the good that YHWH had done to Israel, in that he had delivered them out of the hand of the Egyptians. The Gentile's rejoicing over Israel's deliverance anticipates Paul's appeal to the Gentiles in Rom 15:10 (quoting Deut 32:43): 'Rejoice, O Gentiles, with his people.' The nations' joy at YHWH's saving acts is the eschatological reality that Jethro's response prefigures.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A revelation of God: Jethro said, 'Blessed be YHWH, who has delivered you out of the hand of the Egyptians and out of the hand of Pharaoh and has delivered the people from under the hand of the Egyptians.' The Gentile's doxology — blessing YHWH — is the response that God seeks from all nations. The blessing of YHWH by a non-Israelite priest at the foot of Sinai is one of the most remarkable moments of Gentile worship in the entire Torah.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Now I know that YHWH is greater than all gods, because in this affair they dealt arrogantly with the people.' Jethro's theology is shaped by what YHWH did: the exodus proves YHWH's supremacy over all other divine claims. This is exactly the conclusion the plagues were designed to produce (Exod 7:5; 9:16). Jethro's confession — from outside the covenant — is the paradigm for the recognition that the nations will ultimately give to YHWH through Christ (Phil 2:9-11).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A shadow: Jethro brought a burnt offering and sacrifices to God, and Aaron came with all the elders of Israel to eat bread before God with Moses's father-in-law. A Gentile priest offers sacrifice and presides at a meal with the elders of Israel before God. This covenant meal with a Gentile at the table anticipates the new covenant table of the Lord's Supper, where the dividing wall is abolished and Gentile and Jew eat together (Eph 2:14-16; 1 Cor 11:23-26).</p>",
    "13": "<p>A theme: the next day Moses sat to judge the people, and the people stood around Moses from morning till evening. The sole-mediator burden — Moses bearing all the judicial weight of a nation — reveals both the necessity and the impossibility of single-person mediation. Christ is the one mediator who does not grow weary (1 Tim 2:5; Heb 7:25, 'always living to make intercession'), but the organizational lesson Jethro draws in vv14-26 becomes the structural basis of the church's distributed leadership.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A revelation of God: Jethro asks, 'What is this that you are doing for the people? Why do you sit alone, and all the people stand around you from morning till evening?' The loving, practical concern of a father-in-law for his son-in-law's unsustainable burden reveals wisdom as a gift that God gives through ordinary human relationships. The distribution of wisdom through unexpected sources — here a Gentile — anticipates Paul's body metaphor: different members bear different gifts for the common good (1 Cor 12:7-11).</p>",
    "15": "<p>A theme: Moses answers, 'Because the people come to me to inquire of God; when they have a dispute, they come to me and I decide between one person and another, and I make them know the statutes of God and his laws.' Moses's self-description as the one who brings the people's cases to God and brings God's statutes to the people is the double function of the priest-mediator — intercession upward, instruction downward. Christ fulfills both: interceding for us (Heb 7:25) and teaching us the new covenant's ways (Matt 5-7; Heb 1:2).</p>",
    "16": "<p>A revelation of God: 'When they have a dispute, they come to me and I decide.' The judicial function of Moses — the one who knows God's statutes and applies them — anticipates Christ as the final judge (Acts 17:31; John 5:22,27). But unlike Moses who cannot sustain this role alone, Christ's judgment is perfect, unlimited, and does not require delegation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A revelation of God: Jethro said, 'What you are doing is not good.' The plain-spoken correction of Moses by his Gentile father-in-law — and Moses's receptivity to it — reveals both the humility of true leadership and the democratic character of wisdom in Israel's community. God speaks through a Midianite priest to correct the greatest of Israel's leaders. The Spirit blows where it wills (John 3:8).</p>",
    "18": "<p>A theme: 'You and the people with you will certainly wear out, for the thing is too heavy for you. You are not able to do it alone.' The limit of human mediation — Moses's exhaustion, the people's exhaustion — is the precise point at which the insufficiency of the law-mediator becomes visible. Jethro's diagnosis of structural unsustainability points to the need for the mediator who 'always lives to make intercession' (Heb 7:25) without growing weary.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A theme: 'Listen now to my voice; I will give you advice, and God be with you! You shall represent the people before God and bring their cases to God.' The essential mediatorial role — representing the people before God — is what Moses is called to preserve even as he delegates judicial work. This core intercession is the function Christ preserves eternally. Every other judicial function can be distributed; the Son's intercession before the Father is unique.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A revelation of God: 'and you shall warn them about the statutes and the laws, and make them know the way in which they must walk and what they must do.' The teaching function of the mediator — making the way known — is fulfilled in Christ who is 'the way, and the truth, and the life' (John 14:6). Moses taught the way; Christ is the way.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A theme: choose able men who fear God, who are trustworthy and hate a bribe. The fourfold qualification for leadership — ability, fear of God, trustworthiness, incorruptibility — is the standard for church leadership in the NT (1 Tim 3:1-13; Tit 1:5-9). Jethro's organizational wisdom, delivered by a Gentile, becomes the institutional template for the early church's appointment of deacons (Acts 6:3) and elders.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A theme: let them judge the people at all times, bringing only the hard cases to Moses. The principle of subsidiarity — decisions made at the lowest competent level — reflects a creation order in which different people bear different responsibilities. Paul applies the same principle to the church: the gifted members of the body each bear their own load (Gal 6:5) while the harder cases are brought to the apostolic council (Acts 15).</p>",
    "23": "<p>A revelation of God: 'If you do this, God will direct you, you will be able to endure, and all this people also will go to their place in peace.' Jethro's organizational advice comes with a condition: if you do this — and God directs — then the outcome will be peace for the whole people. The connection between sound structure and shalom is a creation-order principle: God's design for human community when honored produces wellbeing. Disorder and overloading the mediator produces exhaustion and injustice.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A revelation of God: Moses listened to the voice of his father-in-law and did all that he had said. Moses's receptivity to counsel from a Gentile is a model of the humility that characterizes the true servant of God. Christ himself, though the Son, 'learned obedience through what he suffered' (Heb 5:8) — the pattern of learning from others, even in the humility of the incarnation, is rooted in this narrative.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A theme: Moses chose able men out of all Israel and made them heads over the people — rulers of thousands, hundreds, fifties, and tens. The four-tier hierarchy (thousands, hundreds, fifties, tens) creates a scalable structure for a nation of 600,000. The church's organizational polity — elders, deacons, small groups — mirrors this scalable structure. The principle that God's people need ordered community, not only immediate access to the great mediator, runs through both Testaments.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A theme: the able men judged the people at all times; the hard cases they brought to Moses, but any small matter they decided themselves. The delegation of judicial authority while reserving ultimate appeal for the greatest mediator is the structure of the church's relationship to Christ: ordinary matters are handled by the community in Christ's name (Matt 18:15-20); ultimate appeal belongs to him as the final judge (Acts 17:31).</p>",
    "27": "<p>A shadow: Moses let his father-in-law depart, and he went away to his own country. Jethro's departure after his contribution — the meal, the worship, the organizational wisdom — is the departure of the Gentile consultant who has served his purpose and returns to his people. The pattern anticipates the wider mission: Gentiles encounter the God of Israel, acknowledge his supremacy, contribute wisdom, and then carry the testimony back to their own people. 'This is how all the families of the earth shall be blessed' (Gen 12:3) — through encounter with the God of Jacob's servant.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(existing, EXODUS_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus', existing)
    print('Exodus 16-18 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
